 My name's Andrew, I'm one of the pastors here,

5
00:00:08,600 --> 00:00:10,800
 and if you're relatively new to the Vine,

6
00:00:10,800 --> 00:00:12,200
 we're so glad you're with us.

7
00:00:12,200 --> 00:00:15,800
 We're in week two of a four-week series

8
00:00:15,800 --> 00:00:18,800
 on the topic of personal transformation.

9
00:00:18,800 --> 00:00:21,400
 And this idea in scripture

10
00:00:21,400 --> 00:00:23,840
 that one of the primary ministries of Jesus

11
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:26,240
 is to, through His Spirit and His truth,

12
00:00:26,240 --> 00:00:29,000
 take us from the people that we are right now

13
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:30,840
 to the people that He longs for us to be,

14
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:33,440
 the people He's created us to be.

15
00:00:33,440 --> 00:00:37,040
 And we're basing this series in Ezra, the book of Ezra,

16
00:00:37,040 --> 00:00:40,240
 and specifically this moment of pivotal history

17
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:41,400
 for Israel's people,

18
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:44,560
 where they've been taken out of their exile in Babylon,

19
00:00:44,560 --> 00:00:46,400
 the 70 years of exile in Babylon,

20
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:50,160
 and now released by Cyrus, the king of Persia,

21
00:00:50,160 --> 00:00:51,700
 to go back to Jerusalem,

22
00:00:51,700 --> 00:00:53,960
 and they're standing there in the book of Ezra

23
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:56,460
 in the rubble of Jerusalem,

24
00:00:56,460 --> 00:00:58,400
 where Jerusalem, some 70 years before,

25
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:00,600
 had been this glorious city.

26
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:03,100
 The Babylonians had come in, pulled down the wall,

27
00:01:03,100 --> 00:01:06,240
 destroyed the temple, 70 years in exile.

28
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:08,840
 Now the Jewish people back standing

29
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:11,800
 in the rubble of the city they love.

30
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:14,200
 And as they're standing in that rubble,

31
00:01:14,200 --> 00:01:17,300
 they hear the taunts of the enemies around them.

32
00:01:17,300 --> 00:01:21,060
 And those taunts say, "Can you see the rubble around you?

33
00:01:21,060 --> 00:01:24,700
 "Can you see how burnt out the stones are?

34
00:01:24,700 --> 00:01:26,600
 "Can you see what was once glorious

35
00:01:26,600 --> 00:01:28,460
 "now lies in ruin around you?

36
00:01:28,460 --> 00:01:33,460
 "Can life ever come back to these burnt out stones?"

37
00:01:33,460 --> 00:01:37,600
 And we said last week that for Israel, so for us,

38
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:42,840
 that there's things that lie in ruin in us,

39
00:01:42,840 --> 00:01:45,800
 rubble that we're aware of in our own lives.

40
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:48,860
 Perhaps something that's happened to us in the past,

41
00:01:48,860 --> 00:01:50,840
 something that we're not proud of.

42
00:01:50,840 --> 00:01:52,100
 Perhaps the mistakes we've made,

43
00:01:52,100 --> 00:01:55,160
 or maybe mistakes others made to us.

44
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:58,960
 Trauma that's embedded, hurt and shame, failure, pain,

45
00:01:58,960 --> 00:01:59,860
 whatever it might be.

46
00:01:59,860 --> 00:02:01,660
 But I think all of us can recognize

47
00:02:01,660 --> 00:02:04,740
 that there's some things in our lives that lie in ruin.

48
00:02:04,740 --> 00:02:07,960
 Rubble that we're asking ourselves,

49
00:02:07,960 --> 00:02:11,640
 can anything good ever come from this?

50
00:02:11,640 --> 00:02:15,460
 That we wrestle, don't we, with sometimes recognizing

51
00:02:15,460 --> 00:02:16,760
 that we're not the people that we wanna be.

52
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:17,860
 And we think, you know what?

53
00:02:17,860 --> 00:02:19,500
 I can never be the person that I wanna be.

54
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:21,960
 I can never be the person God wants me to be.

55
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:23,440
 'Cause I've got this rubble and this ruin.

56
00:02:23,440 --> 00:02:24,880
 And have you seen it?

57
00:02:24,880 --> 00:02:25,720
 And if you could see it,

58
00:02:25,720 --> 00:02:29,280
 you'd know that nothing good could ever come from this.

59
00:02:29,280 --> 00:02:33,040
 And what we saw last week in Ezra chapter three

60
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:36,180
 is this beautiful moment where the builders

61
00:02:36,180 --> 00:02:40,180
 bring out the first stones to begin to rebuild the temple

62
00:02:40,180 --> 00:02:42,980
 that had been destroyed some 70 years before.

63
00:02:42,980 --> 00:02:43,940
 And as they bring it out,

64
00:02:43,940 --> 00:02:47,580
 there's this sense of that question hanging over Israel.

65
00:02:47,580 --> 00:02:50,340
 Are you going to agree with the taunts of the enemy,

66
00:02:50,340 --> 00:02:53,080
 see the rubble around you and think nothing good

67
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:54,380
 could ever come from it?

68
00:02:54,380 --> 00:02:57,980
 Or are you gonna get a new mindset?

69
00:02:57,980 --> 00:02:59,980
 And then recognize that there is that rubble,

70
00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:03,580
 but believe that in the power and in the mercy of God,

71
00:03:03,580 --> 00:03:06,180
 the rain that falls by the Holy Spirit,

72
00:03:06,180 --> 00:03:08,680
 what was rubble in this moment

73
00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:11,040
 can become a new building in the next.

74
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:14,680
 And last week, I shared with you some ways

75
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:16,720
 in which I think God begins this process

76
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:19,320
 of personal transformation in our lives

77
00:03:19,320 --> 00:03:22,220
 and those areas that we recognize have that ruin

78
00:03:22,220 --> 00:03:23,780
 and that rubble.

79
00:03:23,780 --> 00:03:26,540
 I wanted to summarize four things specifically

80
00:03:26,540 --> 00:03:28,040
 that we talked about last week,

81
00:03:28,040 --> 00:03:31,940
 just to help you get a sense of where we are in this series.

82
00:03:31,940 --> 00:03:32,940
 And then we're gonna go from there.

83
00:03:32,940 --> 00:03:35,040
 Here's the first thing we learned last week.

84
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:38,780
 Any process of personal transformation doesn't begin

85
00:03:38,780 --> 00:03:40,580
 until we take an honest and sober look

86
00:03:40,580 --> 00:03:42,280
 at the rubble that exists in our lives.

87
00:03:42,280 --> 00:03:47,280
 We must understand and own what needs to change within us.

88
00:03:47,580 --> 00:03:49,340
 No one has ever changed or transformed

89
00:03:49,340 --> 00:03:51,000
 without first saying there's something inside of me

90
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,400
 that needs to change.

91
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:55,300
 And it's a sober thing to recognize

92
00:03:55,300 --> 00:03:56,900
 that there is rubble and ruin,

93
00:03:56,900 --> 00:03:58,140
 not to try to hide it,

94
00:03:58,140 --> 00:04:00,300
 not to try to pretend it's not there,

95
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:01,880
 but to say, Lord, I recognize it

96
00:04:01,880 --> 00:04:04,040
 and I know I can't do anything about it,

97
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:06,200
 but Lord, I bring it to you.

98
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:09,300
 We saw last week, number two,

99
00:04:09,300 --> 00:04:12,200
 that God's work of renewal begins in the rubble.

100
00:04:12,200 --> 00:04:14,640
 It's the very place where he does his best work.

101
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:16,480
 He doesn't remove our rubble.

102
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:17,600
 He restores it.

103
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:19,000
 The beautiful thing that we saw last week

104
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,400
 is that those first kind of stones

105
00:04:21,400 --> 00:04:23,040
 that were laid by the builders

106
00:04:23,040 --> 00:04:25,240
 were out of that burnt out rubble

107
00:04:25,240 --> 00:04:27,580
 where people thought nothing good could ever come of that.

108
00:04:27,580 --> 00:04:30,300
 That becomes the stone the builders rejected,

109
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:32,140
 becomes the cornerstone.

110
00:04:32,140 --> 00:04:33,740
 The things in our lives that we think,

111
00:04:33,740 --> 00:04:35,540
 oh man, if only I could just get rid

112
00:04:35,540 --> 00:04:37,300
 of all of that gunk and stuff.

113
00:04:37,300 --> 00:04:39,940
 That's the stuff that God's playground.

114
00:04:39,940 --> 00:04:41,740
 He looks at that stuff in your life.

115
00:04:41,740 --> 00:04:43,340
 He rolls up his sleeves and says,

116
00:04:43,340 --> 00:04:45,040
 come on, we're gonna do something

117
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:48,740
 with what you thought could never be transformed or renewed.

118
00:04:48,740 --> 00:04:51,780
 Thirdly, we saw this last week.

119
00:04:51,780 --> 00:04:54,600
 As Christians, worship must begin a process

120
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,900
 of transformation, not just complete it.

121
00:04:56,900 --> 00:04:58,140
 When we are in the rubble,

122
00:04:58,140 --> 00:05:00,780
 our worship should focus on the character of God

123
00:05:00,780 --> 00:05:03,200
 over the circumstance of the world.

124
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:05,840
 We often worship as a response,

125
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:07,600
 worship out of the overflow

126
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:09,840
 or the outcome of something God's done.

127
00:05:09,840 --> 00:05:11,100
 God's answered that prayer.

128
00:05:11,100 --> 00:05:12,140
 He's come through for me.

129
00:05:12,140 --> 00:05:13,340
 He's done that miracle.

130
00:05:13,340 --> 00:05:15,040
 Out of that, I find worship.

131
00:05:15,040 --> 00:05:16,300
 And that's absolutely right.

132
00:05:16,300 --> 00:05:18,300
 We should worship out of outcome.

133
00:05:18,300 --> 00:05:20,200
 But what we see in Ezra chapter three

134
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:22,080
 is that the Jewish people, the Israelites,

135
00:05:22,080 --> 00:05:25,740
 began worship long before they saw an outcome.

136
00:05:25,740 --> 00:05:28,000
 They lay the foundations of the stone

137
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,600
 through this act of worship, giving praise and glory,

138
00:05:31,600 --> 00:05:34,340
 not because of what they can see with their eyes,

139
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:35,880
 not because of some thing

140
00:05:35,880 --> 00:05:38,140
 that they're expecting God to do in the future.

141
00:05:38,140 --> 00:05:40,580
 They praise for the character of God

142
00:05:40,580 --> 00:05:43,180
 over the circumstance they find themselves in.

143
00:05:43,180 --> 00:05:46,900
 And every move of personal transformation in your life

144
00:05:46,900 --> 00:05:49,980
 will happen as we shift towards this worship

145
00:05:49,980 --> 00:05:54,300
 of his character over our circumstance.

146
00:05:54,300 --> 00:05:55,500
 Not an easy thing to do,

147
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:57,580
 but something glorious when we do it.

148
00:05:57,580 --> 00:05:58,940
 And here's the fourth thing.

149
00:05:58,940 --> 00:06:00,380
 We said this, we must understand

150
00:06:00,380 --> 00:06:02,440
 that God's renewal takes time.

151
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:05,600
 It is a journey of many small, obedient decisions

152
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:07,740
 within a much larger framework

153
00:06:07,740 --> 00:06:09,540
 of God's purposes in our lives.

154
00:06:09,540 --> 00:06:12,200
 We would love a magic wand to be waved

155
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:15,300
 and suddenly that trauma goes, but the reality is

156
00:06:15,300 --> 00:06:17,600
 so often it's those small little steps

157
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:20,080
 that we take each day when we stay obedient

158
00:06:20,080 --> 00:06:22,180
 to the thing that God's called us in our lives,

159
00:06:22,180 --> 00:06:25,700
 that God shapes a masterpiece over time.

160
00:06:25,700 --> 00:06:27,180
 Some of the most important things

161
00:06:27,180 --> 00:06:28,740
 that God will ever do in your life,

162
00:06:28,740 --> 00:06:31,080
 it's gonna take some time.

163
00:06:31,080 --> 00:06:32,480
 And sometimes opening ourselves up

164
00:06:32,480 --> 00:06:35,000
 to the journey of that process

165
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:38,500
 is primary in the season of transformation in our lives.

166
00:06:38,500 --> 00:06:39,700
 So that was last week.

167
00:06:39,700 --> 00:06:40,680
 If you weren't here last week,

168
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,180
 you can jump back online, you can hear it,

169
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:43,800
 or you can just take a photo of that slide and go,

170
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:45,140
 I've got it, all right?

171
00:06:45,140 --> 00:06:48,240
 So last week we focused on this idea

172
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:52,140
 that personal transformation begins with this.

173
00:06:52,140 --> 00:06:55,840
 Today, I wanna talk about, as we continue this passage,

174
00:06:55,840 --> 00:06:58,440
 I wanna talk about the environment

175
00:06:58,440 --> 00:07:01,740
 by which personal transformation truly happens

176
00:07:01,740 --> 00:07:03,980
 and how we here at the Vine might be able

177
00:07:03,980 --> 00:07:07,400
 to create that kind of environment together.

178
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:10,780
 And to tell you about that, I wanna share a quick story.

179
00:07:10,780 --> 00:07:13,480
 In my early 20s, I worked for a recruitment company.

180
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:14,880
 It was a headhunting firm,

181
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:16,640
 an international headhunting company

182
00:07:16,640 --> 00:07:19,640
 that had offices in New York, in Hong Kong, and in Tokyo.

183
00:07:19,640 --> 00:07:22,480
 And it just so happened that when I was about 23 years old,

184
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:24,200
 most of my clients, most of my candidates

185
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:25,840
 were based in Tokyo.

186
00:07:25,840 --> 00:07:28,100
 So every eight weeks, I would have a business trip

187
00:07:28,100 --> 00:07:30,540
 up to Tokyo, and for Monday to Friday,

188
00:07:30,540 --> 00:07:32,740
 I would be in the Tokyo office,

189
00:07:32,740 --> 00:07:34,280
 and I'd be meeting with my clients,

190
00:07:34,280 --> 00:07:35,480
 meeting with my candidates and doing all that.

191
00:07:35,480 --> 00:07:36,540
 Then I'd come back to Hong Kong.

192
00:07:36,540 --> 00:07:38,800
 But on this one particular trip,

193
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:42,300
 the company up in Japan asked me to stay for two weeks,

194
00:07:42,300 --> 00:07:43,980
 which meant that I was gonna, for the first time,

195
00:07:43,980 --> 00:07:46,780
 stay over the weekend in Tokyo.

196
00:07:46,780 --> 00:07:50,580
 And I had come to Christ about three years prior to this.

197
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:52,700
 So I came to Jesus at university

198
00:07:52,700 --> 00:07:54,580
 when I was in my early 20s.

199
00:07:54,580 --> 00:07:58,480
 Now I'm 23, I'm in Tokyo, I'm staying over the weekend.

200
00:07:58,480 --> 00:08:00,980
 And I decided I wanted to go and visit a church,

201
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:03,680
 not knowing anything really about the Christian context

202
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:06,180
 in Japan or about churches in general.

203
00:08:06,180 --> 00:08:07,340
 And you also have to remember,

204
00:08:07,340 --> 00:08:08,640
 I'm kind of dating myself here,

205
00:08:08,640 --> 00:08:12,340
 but this was quite a while ago, okay, when I was 23.

206
00:08:12,340 --> 00:08:15,380
 So the interwebs was not quite the thing that it is today.

207
00:08:15,380 --> 00:08:18,200
 It existed, okay, we used it,

208
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:19,600
 but there was no Google Maps,

209
00:08:19,600 --> 00:08:21,200
 there was no kind of stuff like that,

210
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:22,780
 none of that existed yet.

211
00:08:22,780 --> 00:08:24,240
 So I did the smart thing,

212
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:26,680
 I turned to my Japanese colleague in the office,

213
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:29,380
 and I said, "Hey, would you make some phone calls for me

214
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:32,540
 "and find out if there's a church near where I'm staying?"

215
00:08:32,540 --> 00:08:34,840
 And he's like, "Oh, I'm just on, I'm just on, okay, okay."

216
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:36,700
 (audience laughing)

217
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:38,340
 So he makes some phone calls across the day,

218
00:08:38,340 --> 00:08:39,400
 and at the end of the day, he comes to me,

219
00:08:39,400 --> 00:08:40,500
 he's like, "Oh, Andrew-san," he goes,

220
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:42,000
 "I find a church for you."

221
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,080
 And I'm like, "Oh, that's great."

222
00:08:43,080 --> 00:08:44,500
 He's like, "It's only a 10-minute walk

223
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:47,000
 "from your hotel where you're staying, fantastic."

224
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,900
 He says, "It's on the 14th floor of this industrial building,"

225
00:08:49,900 --> 00:08:52,980
 and he gave me the details, he wrote it all out for me.

226
00:08:52,980 --> 00:08:54,200
 So sure enough, on the Sunday,

227
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:56,340
 I think the service started at like 9.30 or 10,

228
00:08:56,340 --> 00:08:58,800
 I can't fully remember, but I was there on time,

229
00:08:58,800 --> 00:09:00,340
 got in the lift, I went up,

230
00:09:00,340 --> 00:09:02,780
 the doors of the lift opened on the 14th floor,

231
00:09:02,780 --> 00:09:05,480
 and I looked at what was in front of me,

232
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:07,140
 and I immediately began to think,

233
00:09:07,140 --> 00:09:09,580
 I might need to fire my colleague.

234
00:09:09,580 --> 00:09:12,140
 (audience laughing)

235
00:09:12,140 --> 00:09:16,240
 In front of me was this old Japanese lady, beautiful lady,

236
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:19,400
 probably in her late 70s, early 80s,

237
00:09:19,400 --> 00:09:22,500
 wearing a very formal Japanese outfit,

238
00:09:22,500 --> 00:09:24,680
 hunched a little bit because of her age.

239
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:28,580
 When she saw the doors open, her eyes just lit up.

240
00:09:28,580 --> 00:09:30,200
 She was so excited.

241
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:33,700
 She's like, "A foreigner has come to our church.

242
00:09:33,700 --> 00:09:36,940
 Like revival is breaking out."

243
00:09:36,940 --> 00:09:39,280
 And she gives me like this little brochure

244
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:40,880
 that was all in Japanese.

245
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:43,900
 She opens this door and leads me into this room.

246
00:09:43,900 --> 00:09:44,840
 I go into this room,

247
00:09:44,840 --> 00:09:47,380
 there's probably about 50 chairs in this room,

248
00:09:47,380 --> 00:09:49,200
 a small kind of room, about 50 chairs.

249
00:09:49,200 --> 00:09:52,300
 There's about 15 people standing in the room.

250
00:09:52,300 --> 00:09:55,140
 As I come in, all 15 people turn around,

251
00:09:55,140 --> 00:09:58,100
 and I immediately realized that the youngest person

252
00:09:58,100 --> 00:10:01,440
 in that room other than me was probably about 78.

253
00:10:01,440 --> 00:10:03,140
 (audience laughing)

254
00:10:03,140 --> 00:10:05,880
 And they were all super like conservative,

255
00:10:05,880 --> 00:10:08,100
 old Japanese people.

256
00:10:08,100 --> 00:10:10,500
 And they all stared at me with eyes lit up,

257
00:10:10,500 --> 00:10:11,640
 just like the lady at the entrance,

258
00:10:11,640 --> 00:10:12,740
 and they all rushed over me.

259
00:10:12,740 --> 00:10:14,200
 And it was that awkward moment,

260
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:15,700
 when you're not Japanese, you don't know what to do.

261
00:10:15,700 --> 00:10:17,180
 It's like, do you bow?

262
00:10:17,180 --> 00:10:18,500
