00:21:07,480 --> 00:21:09,800
 that they've already lost.

523
00:21:09,800 --> 00:21:15,680
 I wonder if that resonates with any of you here.

524
00:21:15,680 --> 00:21:17,540
 I know it does for me.

525
00:21:17,540 --> 00:21:20,780
 I know it's quite easy to think that my best years

526
00:21:20,780 --> 00:21:24,140
 of my life are already in the rear view mirror.

527
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:26,880
 Like those moments back in the old days.

528
00:21:26,880 --> 00:21:28,780
 Some people in my generation and above,

529
00:21:28,780 --> 00:21:30,280
 we have this phrase, if you're young here,

530
00:21:30,280 --> 00:21:31,340
 it will annoy you, I'm sure.

531
00:21:31,340 --> 00:21:32,640
 And you've heard it many times.

532
00:21:32,640 --> 00:21:34,200
 Oh, in our day.

533
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:37,840
 Well, if only you'd been in my time.

534
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:39,400
 In our day, there was no social media.

535
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:40,780
 People actually talked to each other.

536
00:21:40,780 --> 00:21:42,400
 It was great.

537
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:44,540
 We actually had community in my day,

538
00:21:44,540 --> 00:21:45,640
 you know, whatever it might be.

539
00:21:45,640 --> 00:21:47,340
 Like we know what it's like, isn't it?

540
00:21:47,340 --> 00:21:51,800
 To look back on the past with rose tinted spectacles.

541
00:21:51,800 --> 00:21:53,880
 To look back and go, oh man, I remember those days.

542
00:21:53,880 --> 00:21:54,740
 Oh, that was great.

543
00:21:54,740 --> 00:21:58,280
 It's not so great anymore, but it was awesome back there.

544
00:21:58,280 --> 00:22:01,140
 We do this not just in terms of history and experience.

545
00:22:01,140 --> 00:22:03,780
 We do this in terms of relationships.

546
00:22:03,780 --> 00:22:05,740
 How many of us here might be honest and say,

547
00:22:05,740 --> 00:22:08,980
 man, I wish my husband would be like he was

548
00:22:08,980 --> 00:22:10,240
 when we first got married.

549
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:15,040
 I wish my relationship was as romantic

550
00:22:15,040 --> 00:22:17,880
 as it was when we first started dating.

551
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:20,480
 Now it feels like my spouse doesn't even look at me.

552
00:22:20,480 --> 00:22:22,740
 As humans, we have this tendency

553
00:22:22,740 --> 00:22:24,920
 to always look back on the things in the past

554
00:22:24,920 --> 00:22:27,020
 with these rose colored glasses,

555
00:22:27,020 --> 00:22:29,680
 kind of being selective about what we remember

556
00:22:29,680 --> 00:22:32,140
 and trying to pull that to kind of say something

557
00:22:32,140 --> 00:22:33,320
 about what it is today.

558
00:22:33,320 --> 00:22:37,240
 But when you look back and all your focus is back

559
00:22:37,240 --> 00:22:39,440
 to the glory of something in the past,

560
00:22:39,440 --> 00:22:40,520
 here's what happens.

561
00:22:40,520 --> 00:22:42,620
 You become blind to the importance

562
00:22:42,620 --> 00:22:44,840
 of your presence in future.

563
00:22:44,840 --> 00:22:48,040
 You just get consumed by all this stuff over here

564
00:22:48,040 --> 00:22:50,120
 and it stops you from actually moving forward.

565
00:22:50,120 --> 00:22:53,120
 See, in seasons of personal transformation,

566
00:22:53,120 --> 00:22:55,940
 it's tempting to idolize the past,

567
00:22:55,940 --> 00:22:58,740
 demonize the presence and fear the future.

568
00:22:58,740 --> 00:23:02,520
 It's really tempting for us to do that.

569
00:23:02,520 --> 00:23:05,240
 And this is, I think, what the older Israelites

570
00:23:05,240 --> 00:23:08,240
 and the priests are in danger of doing in this moment.

571
00:23:08,240 --> 00:23:09,840
 They're idolizing the past.

572
00:23:09,840 --> 00:23:12,420
 Oh man, if you had seen that previous temple,

573
00:23:12,420 --> 00:23:14,540
 if you had seen the power that was there,

574
00:23:14,540 --> 00:23:18,480
 oh, and you think this is good, you're worshiping to this?

575
00:23:18,480 --> 00:23:20,380
 It's like me in that church in Japan.

576
00:23:20,380 --> 00:23:23,080
 Really, you guys, you're worshiping to this?

577
00:23:23,080 --> 00:23:25,840
 And there's this moment, isn't there,

578
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:28,280
 where we bring the baggage and we say,

579
00:23:28,280 --> 00:23:29,980
 well, if it's not like it was back then,

580
00:23:29,980 --> 00:23:31,280
 well, it can't be any good.

581
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:32,520
 And the priests and the Levites,

582
00:23:32,520 --> 00:23:35,520
 they're in danger in this moment of weeping

583
00:23:35,520 --> 00:23:39,240
 from completely missing the new thing God wants to do.

584
00:23:40,240 --> 00:23:42,920
 And they're so connected back to the pain

585
00:23:42,920 --> 00:23:45,180
 of what they've lost that they can't even see

586
00:23:45,180 --> 00:23:47,020
 what they're about to gain.

587
00:23:47,020 --> 00:23:49,220
 Not only that, but I think they're also in danger

588
00:23:49,220 --> 00:23:52,440
 of wanting to stop the others from building.

589
00:23:52,440 --> 00:23:55,440
 Like, there's no point even trying.

590
00:23:55,440 --> 00:23:56,480
 We can't get back.

591
00:23:56,480 --> 00:23:57,740
 That was the glorious moment.

592
00:23:57,740 --> 00:23:58,680
 That was the great temple.

593
00:23:58,680 --> 00:24:00,480
 Look, just put your tools down.

594
00:24:00,480 --> 00:24:01,880
 There's no spirit here.

595
00:24:01,880 --> 00:24:03,320
 There's no power here.

596
00:24:03,320 --> 00:24:04,380
 Let's just give up.

597
00:24:04,380 --> 00:24:06,480
 We're just singing words without anything.

598
00:24:06,480 --> 00:24:08,960
 They're in danger of allowing the missing

599
00:24:08,960 --> 00:24:11,220
 of the thing in the past to actually begin to say,

600
00:24:11,220 --> 00:24:12,680
 we're not even gonna bother to move forward

601
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:13,520
 with the present.

602
00:24:13,520 --> 00:24:20,020
 See, when you allow the grief of your past

603
00:24:20,020 --> 00:24:21,860
 to continue to speak louder to you

604
00:24:21,860 --> 00:24:23,460
 than the hope of your future,

605
00:24:23,460 --> 00:24:25,980
 you are always going to end up in a situation

606
00:24:25,980 --> 00:24:29,960
 where you're likely to resist and to not embrace

607
00:24:29,960 --> 00:24:32,820
 the very transformation that God wants to do in your life.

608
00:24:35,060 --> 00:24:37,460
 And in this moment, I think this is where

609
00:24:37,460 --> 00:24:41,660
 these older people are, two feet here,

610
00:24:41,660 --> 00:24:46,660
 and God's here saying, watch what I'm about to do.

611
00:24:46,660 --> 00:24:50,760
 But we can actually resist the transformation

612
00:24:50,760 --> 00:24:52,420
 God wants to bring us.

613
00:24:52,420 --> 00:24:53,860
 If we're trying to get ourselves back

614
00:24:53,860 --> 00:24:56,460
 to an old version of ourselves.

615
00:24:56,460 --> 00:24:58,520
 The Hebrew word for restoration in scripture

616
00:24:58,520 --> 00:24:59,820
 is not go back.

617
00:24:59,820 --> 00:25:01,760
 You know, like you think about it with a car.

618
00:25:01,760 --> 00:25:03,860
 What is it like to restore an old car?

619
00:25:03,860 --> 00:25:07,160
 The idea is to make it look as good as it did originally.

620
00:25:07,160 --> 00:25:08,620
 That's not the Hebrew word.

621
00:25:08,620 --> 00:25:11,460
 Restoration in scripture is not about trying to get you back

622
00:25:11,460 --> 00:25:13,520
 to the perfect image of the thing in the past.

623
00:25:13,520 --> 00:25:16,820
 It's actually about taking you forward to the new thing.

624
00:25:16,820 --> 00:25:19,760
 Paul would say, anybody who is in Christ Jesus is what?

625
00:25:19,760 --> 00:25:20,920
 A new creation.

626
00:25:20,920 --> 00:25:23,520
 The old is gone, the new has come.

627
00:25:23,520 --> 00:25:25,620
 But here's the older people in Israel,

628
00:25:25,620 --> 00:25:28,420
 and they're weeping for what has been lost

629
00:25:28,420 --> 00:25:32,220
 when God's saying, can't you see what you're about to gain?

630
00:25:32,220 --> 00:25:33,980
 Now, stay with me for a second,

631
00:25:33,980 --> 00:25:38,980
 because I'm not saying that weeping is wrong.

632
00:25:38,980 --> 00:25:41,780
 I'm not saying that mourning is bad,

633
00:25:41,780 --> 00:25:44,460
 that we shouldn't feel emotions and hurt and pain,

634
00:25:44,460 --> 00:25:45,680
 and we shouldn't process that.

635
00:25:45,680 --> 00:25:47,880
 In fact, it's completely the opposite of that.

636
00:25:47,880 --> 00:25:51,220
 Scripture has so much to say about the wonder

637
00:25:51,220 --> 00:25:53,860
 of what it is for us humans to feel and have emotion

638
00:25:53,860 --> 00:25:55,680
 and to know pain and to know trauma,

639
00:25:55,680 --> 00:25:57,820
 and to have to try to process it.

640
00:25:57,820 --> 00:25:59,220
 Jesus in the Sermon on the Mount,

641
00:25:59,220 --> 00:26:01,480
 Matthew 5, 4 says to everybody around him,

642
00:26:01,480 --> 00:26:04,420
 he said, "Blessed are those who mourn,

643
00:26:04,420 --> 00:26:06,580
 for they will be comforted."

644
00:26:06,580 --> 00:26:09,120
 In other words, it's okay to have pain.

645
00:26:09,120 --> 00:26:11,060
 It's okay to look back and go,

646
00:26:11,060 --> 00:26:13,460
 man, that was something great there that I've lost.

647
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:17,760
 It's all right to feel the disappointment and the hurt.

648
00:26:17,760 --> 00:26:20,320
 In fact, the Christian religion

649
00:26:20,320 --> 00:26:22,720
 is one of the most beautiful religions,

650
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:26,460
 because rather than trying to simply explain our suffering,

651
00:26:26,460 --> 00:26:28,180
 the Christian religion has a God

652
00:26:28,180 --> 00:26:30,320
 who joins us in that suffering.

653
00:26:31,320 --> 00:26:32,460
 That's a radical thing.

654
00:26:32,460 --> 00:26:33,600
 There's no other religion,

655
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:36,160
 there's no other faith in the world where that happens,

656
00:26:36,160 --> 00:26:38,460
 where God will come and be a part of the pain

657
00:26:38,460 --> 00:26:40,160
 and the suffering of this world.

658
00:26:40,160 --> 00:26:43,460
 Jesus himself weeps out loud bitterly

659
00:26:43,460 --> 00:26:45,860
 when his best friend, Lazarus, dies.

660
00:26:45,860 --> 00:26:49,560
 He feels the pain and he doesn't try to hide it,

661
00:26:49,560 --> 00:26:53,200
 even though he knows he's about to bring him back to life.

662
00:26:53,200 --> 00:26:55,460
 Get your head around that one for a moment.

663
00:26:55,460 --> 00:26:57,900
 He weeps in the Garden of Gethsemane,

664
00:26:57,900 --> 00:27:00,100
 knowing the weight of what it's going to be

665
00:27:00,100 --> 00:27:02,360
 to take the sin of the world on his shoulders

666
00:27:02,360 --> 00:27:04,560
 and a desperate cry before his father

667
00:27:04,560 --> 00:27:05,960
 if there's any other way.

668
00:27:05,960 --> 00:27:08,620
 And he weeps and weeps in that moment.

669
00:27:08,620 --> 00:27:11,100
 And yet he knows that the Lord, his father,

670
00:27:11,100 --> 00:27:13,660
 is still going to be glorified.

671
00:27:13,660 --> 00:27:14,920
 He knows the victory is there,

672
00:27:14,920 --> 00:27:17,000
 but he still finds a place to weep.

673
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:19,620
 This is the beautiful thing about our faith.

674
00:27:19,620 --> 00:27:24,020
 In Jesus, we do not just have a God of the sufferers,

675
00:27:24,020 --> 00:27:26,220
 we have a God who suffers.

676
00:27:26,220 --> 00:27:28,220
 Come on, church.

677
00:27:29,620 --> 00:27:30,920
 That's a profound thought.

678
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:36,860
 That means that in my suffering, in my pain, in my hurt,

679
00:27:36,860 --> 00:27:39,420
 in the things that I'm holding in my spirit,

680
00:27:39,420 --> 00:27:41,760
 I've got a God who understands that.

681
00:27:41,760 --> 00:27:43,520
 I've got a God who's not sitting on a cloud going,

682
00:27:43,520 --> 00:27:45,820
 oh yeah, yeah, you suffer, that must be hard.

683
00:27:45,820 --> 00:27:48,500
 I've got a God who's walked in my shoes,

684
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:50,600
 knows that pain, felt it himself,

685
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:52,760
 worse than I will ever find it.

686
00:27:52,760 --> 00:27:54,800
 And so I have somebody to turn to

687
00:27:54,800 --> 00:27:56,560
 who understands what's going on in my life

688
00:27:56,560 --> 00:27:58,760
 and can meet me in the reality of the pain

689
00:27:58,760 --> 00:28:03,000
 and the brokenness that I feel that liberates me to mourn,

690
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:04,920
 that allows me to bring my grief.

691
00:28:04,920 --> 00:28:07,720
 This is why we have the lament Psalms in the Psalms.

692
00:28:07,720 --> 00:28:09,720
 It's why we have these beautiful poems

693
00:28:09,720 --> 00:28:12,700
 where God's people say, why have you forsaken me?

694
00:28:12,700 --> 00:28:13,920
 Where are you, God?

695
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:15,060
 Why have you left me?

696
00:28:15,060 --> 00:28:16,000
 Why have you gone?

697
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:18,560
 And we begin to have these beautiful expressions.

698
00:28:18,560 --> 00:28:20,760
 And if I was writing the Bible and putting it together,

699
00:28:20,760 --> 00:28:23,000
 I would have taken those things and left them out.

700
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:24,860
 Like, oh, that's a bit harsh.

701
00:28:24,860 --> 00:28:26,360
 You can't speak to God that way.

702
00:28:26,360 --> 00:28:28,020
 Let's just put that one aside.

703
00:28:28,020 --> 00:28:31,760
 No, no, they're in the scriptures to give us permission

704
00:28:31,760 --> 00:28:34,420
 to bring our big feelings to God,

705
00:28:34,420 --> 00:28:37,000
 to not bury them under the ground or try to push them away

706
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:38,360
 or pretend that they're not there.

707
00:28:38,360 --> 00:28:41,320
 We have a God who's joined us in our suffering.

708
00:28:41,320 --> 00:28:44,960
 Our suffering always has a place with him.

709
00:28:44,960 --> 00:28:47,660
 I don't need to run from it.

710
00:28:47,660 --> 00:28:49,120
 I don't need to hide from it.

711
00:28:49,120 --> 00:28:53,500
 Equally though, I don't need to let it overwhelm me

712
00:28:53,500 --> 00:28:54,920
 to the point where I can no longer see

713
00:28:54,920 --> 00:28:56,720
 what God's doing in the midst of it.

714
00:28:57,660 --> 00:28:58,500
 - Yeah.

715
00:28:58,500 --> 00:29:02,420
 - You see, when we weep before God, here's what we do.

716
00:29:02,420 --> 00:29:06,360
 We acknowledge our humanity and his divinity.

717
00:29:06,360 --> 00:29:11,000
 We proclaim through our tears, faith and trust

718
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:13,660
 that he alone is able to comfort and heal.

719
00:29:13,660 --> 00:29:17,500
 That's the wonder of what it is to weep.

720
00:29:17,500 --> 00:29:19,800
 That's the beauty of what it is to offer it.

721
00:29:19,800 --> 00:29:23,460
 And in this moment, yes, I do think that they're weeping

722
00:29:23,460 --> 00:29:25,220
 because of what they feel they've lost.

723
00:29:25,220 --> 00:29:26,960
 But I think there's a bigger point

724
00:29:26,960 --> 00:29:28,500
 to their weeping in this moment.

725
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:32,120
 They're weeping because they realize

726
00:29:32,120 --> 00:29:35,160
 that they are aligning themselves to the pain

727
00:29:35,160 --> 00:29:36,660
 that is on the father's heart.

728
00:29:36,660 --> 00:29:39,120
 You see, they're weeping for what I would argue

729
00:29:39,120 --> 00:29:41,660
 is something called godly sorrow.

730
00:29:41,660 --> 00:29:44,960
 Got to remember the history again.

731
00:29:44,960 --> 00:29:47,200
 For 70 years, they're in exile.

732
00:29:47,200 --> 00:29:49,560
 And during that time, they're reflecting

733
00:29:49,560 --> 00:29:51,420
 and they're thinking about what happened.

734
00:29:51,420 --> 00:29:53,620
 And they're asking one critical question.

735
00:29:53,620 --> 00:29:57,460
 Why did the walls come down around Jerusalem?

736
00:29:57,460 --> 00:30:00,420
 Why did the temple get destroyed?

737
00:30:00,420 --> 00:30:02,620
 And the prophets and the artisans

738
00:30:02,620 --> 00:30:05,620
 and the writers of the Psalms in that time, Psalm 131,

739
00:30:05,620 --> 00:30:07,820
 "By the rivers of Babylon, we sat and wept

740
00:30:07,820 --> 00:30:10,520
 when we remembered Zion."

741
00:30:10,520 --> 00:30:12,520
 Their writers and their poets and their artists

742
00:30:12,520 --> 00:30:14,560
 helped them to understand that the reason

743
00:30:14,560 --> 00:30:18,100
 why they're in exile is not because God's abandoned them,

744
00:30:18,100 --> 00:30:19,900
 not because God's turned his back on them,

745
00:30:19,900 --> 00:30:21,360
 which is what they thought originally.

746
00:30:21,360 --> 00:30:23,360
 But as they process it, think about it,

747
00:30:23,360 --> 00:30:24,860
 spiritually God speaks in them,

748
00:30:24,860 --> 00:30:29,520
 they realize they're in that place because of their choices.

749
00:30:29,520 --> 00:30:34,460
 And the prophets begin to say, "Idolatry and injustice."

750
00:30:34,460 --> 00:30:37,020
 Idolatry in terms of how they were sharing their heart

751
00:30:37,020 --> 00:30:40,200
 no longer with Yahweh, but with other gods and deities.

752
00:30:40,200 --> 00:30:43,160
 Injustice where through that, they were treating themselves

753
00:30:43,160 --> 00:30:45,860
 and others around them poorly and wrongly.

754
00:30:45,860 --> 00:30:48,060
 And because idolatry and injustice

755
00:30:48,060 --> 00:30:52,420
 was so ripe in their midst, God brings the actions,

756
00:30:52,420 --> 00:30:56,200
 the consequences to their sinful choices.

757
00:30:56,200 --> 00:30:59,660
 And I think what's happening here for the older priests,

758
00:30:59,660 --> 00:31:02,300
 as they're standing in the rubble, they're weeping,

759
00:31:02,300 --> 00:31:04,760
 not just because they feel like they've lost something,

760
00:31:04,760 --> 00:31:09,760
 they're weeping because they realize this is our fault.

761
00:31:09,760 --> 00:31:15,920
 We did this, us.

762
00:31:15,920 --> 00:31:18,300
 And I think there's something happening in their hearts

763
00:31:18,300 --> 00:31:20,600
 that is aligning them to the heart of God.

764
00:31:20,600 --> 00:31:24,400
 They're beginning to see sin the way that God sees it,

765
00:31:24,400 --> 00:31:27,160
 and they're beginning to bring these tears of repentance.

766
00:31:27,160 --> 00:31:30,200
 These beautiful, this is not the kind of tears of like,

767
00:31:30,200 --> 00:31:32,460
 "Oh my gosh, I'm so bad, I've screwed up,

768
00:31:32,460 --> 00:31:34,260
 I'm such a terrible person."

769
00:31:34,260 --> 00:31:38,960
 This is like, I see finally what God sees about brokenness

770
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:42,460
 and idolatry and injustice, and it is not right.

771
00:31:42,460 --> 00:31:45,320
 And it breaks my heart like it breaks God's heart.

772
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:46,960
 And it breaks me even more

773
00:31:46,960 --> 00:31:49,800
 'cause I realized I was the one that did this.

774
00:31:49,800 --> 00:31:53,220
 And Lord, I weep because as I look at the rubble,

775
00:31:53,220 --> 00:31:57,060
 I know that we brought the walls down.

776
00:31:57,060 --> 00:32:03,760
 And this profound sense of godly sorrow,

777
00:32:03,760 --> 00:32:06,760
 not to beat myself up 'cause I'm the worst in the world,

778
00:32:06,760 --> 00:32:11,660
 but a beautiful recognition that I finally agree with God,

779
00:32:11,660 --> 00:32:15,300
